2b24b847b34f132f/original/GettyImages-1296312031_WEB.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Sleep</span> <!-- -->May 2, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>Is Sleeping on the Floor Good for Your Back?</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p><i>Scientific American</i> asked experts whether sleeping on a hard surface is actually beneficial for back pain</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Matt Fuchs</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/how-some-common-medications-can-make-people-more-vulnerable-to-heat/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Pharmaceuticals"><img alt="Stock photograph of Asian female model appearing to be overheated, sweating, with one hand placed on chest" class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/3d0c1e9ff1ea6470/original/GettyImages-1325593216_WEB.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Pharmaceuticals</span> <!-- -->May 1, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>How Some Common Medications Can Make People More Vulnerable to Heat</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>As climate change brings more intense heat waves, scientists are trying to understand how certain medications interact with the body&rsquo;s thermoregulation system</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Charlotte Hu</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/longest-ever-covid-infection-lasted-more-than-600-days/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Epidemiology"><img alt="Digital illustration a COVID-19 cell with OMICRON variant, mutated and emerging from the original cell" class="articleImg-L