e/can-food-work-as-medicine/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Health"><img alt="A person in a lab coat and a stethoscope writes in a notebook, with foods like bell peppers and lettuce in the foreground." class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/4e556f6b2277ee54/original/food-medicine-GettyImages-1082939336-loop.gif?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Health</span> <!-- -->May 1, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>Can Food Work as Medicine?</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>Doctors are starting to prescribe vegetables or entire meals to ward off disease.</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Tanya Lewis, Josh Fischman, Elah Feder, Madison Goldberg</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/nearsightedness-rates-are-soaring-heres-why/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Health Care"><img alt="Young girl with blond hair and green short getting eye exam with phoropter." class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/45053d9a67f01ffb/original/GettyImages-173596505.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Health Care</span> <!-- -->April 30, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>Nearsightedness Rates Are Soaring. Here&rsquo;s Why</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>Myopia is becoming so common some people deem it &ldquo;epidemic.&rdquo; Here&rsquo;s why getting kids outside and treating nearsightedness early is crucial for healthy eyesight</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Andrew Herbert, The Conversation US</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href=